content:
Certainly! To achieve the desired styling for the text "BigText" with responsiveness and a hover effect, you can use CSS media queries to adjust the font size according to different screen sizes. Below is the CSS code that applies these requirements:

```css
.big-text {
  font-weight: bold;
  font-size: 27pt; /* Default size increased by 3pt from a base of 24pt */
  transition: color 0.3s ease; /* Smooth transition for hover effect */
}

/* Hover effect */
.big-text:hover {
  color: red;
}

/* Responsive font sizes */
@media (max-width: 575px) {
  .big-text {
    font-size: 24pt;
  }
}

@media (min-width: 576px) and (max-width: 768px) {
  .big-text {
    font-size: 30pt;
  }
}

@media (min-width: 769px) and (max-width: 992px) {
  .big-text {
    font-size: 36pt;
  }
}

@media (min-width: 993px) and (max-width: 1200px) {
  .big-text {
    font-size: 42pt;
  }
}

@media (min-width: 1201px) {
  .big-text {
    font-size: 48pt;
  }
}
```

### Explanation:

1. **Bold and Default Font Size**: The `.big-text` class initially sets the font to be bold and increases the default font size by 3pt to 27pt.

2. **Hover Effect**: The text color changes to red when hovered over, with a smooth transition effect.

3. **Responsive Font Sizes**: Media queries adjust the font size based on the screen width:
   - Less than 576px: 24pt
   - Between 576px and 768px: 30pt
   - Between 769px and 992px: 36pt
   - Between 993px and 1200px: 42pt
   - Greater than 1200px: 48pt

This code will ensure that the "BigText" remains bold, has an increased font size by 3pt, changes color on hover, and adapts to various screen sizes as specified.
